I am rebuilding my framework. And I would love to get some feedback on my thoughts. Also, I&#39;m uncertain of how I should implement authorization.

**What I aim form.**

I aim to get it testable, and I want to include best practices. At the same time, I want it to be quick and easy to set up new pages and develop new features.

**Previously**

My former framework had too much responsibility in the `Controller`. The `Controller` loaded the models and defined the `View`. Something (I wrongly) learned on the web. 

It was quick to add a page. Just add a controller, define the view template, and the router did its job. We had a working page. And if the `Controller` extended the auth controller, the page would only be available for logged-in users.

**My understanding**

Let&#39;s say I have a simple HTML page like this:

    &lt;h1&gt;Hi, I&#39;m a static HTML page&lt;/h1&gt;

In my case, this is a template.html file, and I have a `View` class with a method like this.

    class View {
        ...
        public function output() {
    	    echo $this-&gt;template-&gt;get();
        }
        ...
    }

This View requires no controller, as we have no interaction, except for a URL request which my router will handle. And we certainly don&#39;t want any Model.

Now let me make this reusable and include a `ViewModel`.

    class ViewModel&#160;{
        public function setTitle() {
            $this-&gt;title = &quot;Hi, I&#39;m now a reusable template&quot;;
        }
    }

Then I&#39;ll update the template and the `View` and make the `View` dependent on this `ViewModel`. I&#39;ll spare you the details.

Yet we don&#39;t need any `Controller`. But now, let me include one.

    class Controller {
        public function index( ViewModel $model ) {
            if( isset($_GET[&#39;name&#39;]) {
                $model-&gt;setTitle( &quot;Hi {$_GET[&#39;name&#39;]}, you can now control the title&quot;);
            }
            return $model;
        }
    }

Here I have given the `Model` to the `Controller` as a required argument. It will return an updated `Model`, which I then will deliver to the `View`. 

Why should the `View` and `Controller` be given a shared instance of a model? I would always run the `Controller` before the `View` anyway. Also, this will make it immutable, from my understanding. 

I could load everything like this:

    $model = new ViewModel;
    $controller = new Controller;
    $model = $controller-&gt;index($model);
    $view = new View($model);
    return $view-&gt;output();

In doing so, I have eliminated the need for passing the `Model` to the constructor in the `Controller`. I favor this since I can quickly add multiple actions in a single `Controller`.

    class Controller {
        public function index( ViewModel $model ) {
            // Do something
            return $model;	
        }
    
        public function save( SaveModel $model) {
            // Save request
            return $model;
        }
    }

If using constructors, instead of arguments, it would require me to split those controllers into separate files. If I didn&#39;t do so, the `Controller` could have multiple dependencies that the requested action never uses.

We could argue that this approach to joining controllers will make the controllers less reusable (or more complicated to reuse). But in my case, using a [Convention over Configuration][1] approach, the router will automatically find and load the M, V, and C based on the given URL path. So reusability is not the aim here. Or do you have any thoughts on how to make a pattern like this reusable?

In short; In MVC, MVVC (or MVP if you like), there isn&#39;t always a need for a `Model` and a `Controller`. And sometimes we don&#39;t need the `View`. For instance, if I would log in a user, I would pass this request to a `Controller`, then a `Model`. And if successful, I would redirect them to a dashboard. 

But where does authorization take place? 

**Authorization**

We surely must have an authentication service, a model. What I&#39;m referring to is the validation of a request, to see if the one requesting the route has necessary permissions.

Many argue that we should run authorize in the `Controller`. That&#39;s fine. I would probably end up with some empty controllers classes. Controllers that exist only to extend an authorization controller, which has a callable method I can use to check if the request can proceed.

Adding models to `Controller` through arguments, like the example above, I at least don&#39;t have to create an empty controller for every page. Usually, we should find some controller methods in the class.

A route like `product/info` would then have a `productController` class shared among all product pages. So calling an authorization check wouldn&#39;t be too troublesome, even though the info page does not need any `Controller`.

Here&#39;s an example where a group of pages doesn&#39;t need any controllers, but where I want to limit the path to logged-in users.
 

    class Changelog extends \Controllers\Authenticated {}


    class Authenticated {
    
        private $auth;
    
        public function __construct( Auth $auth ) {
            $this-auth = $auth;
        }
    
        /** Only allow request if auth check is true. */
        public function before() {
            return $this-&gt;auth-&gt;check();
        }
    
    }

It&#39;s all fine. But from my understanding, controllers should be as thin as possible. And its job is to cause models to change state based on the request. An authorization check will make the `Controller` fatter, and the `Model` does not alter any state. It&#39;s merely there to allow a View or actions.

Here is one way I find this troublesome. Let&#39;s say I decide to restructure my controllers to be more reusable. For example, if I have a controller class that is responsible for altering the state of any provided data table model. Would it make sense to introduce another controller that does not involve any controlling, just allowing? Or could we say it controls the request by granting access or denying it?

We surely don&#39;t want to do the authorization check in the `View`. Because, to do so, we have allowed both controllers and models to run before the authorization is approved. 

I don&#39;t believe this belongs to a `Model` or a `ViewModel`, either. If we need to validate access to certain parts of a view (in a `ViewModel`) or limit some elements in a model, then I believe we can include authorization.

Some would suggest a [decorator pattern][2] where we wrap the request in an authorization check. And only proceed if we are allowed. I believe this could be a better solution when it comes to separation of concerns. 

But this requires me to define every route. It also adds another layer to the framework. It increases the complexity by requiring yet another place to be configured to get a page up and running. Also, since we might forget to define it, we must not allow anything that isn&#39;t specified.  The latter would also be true for controller-authorization, but it&#39;s easier not to forget when there are fewer layers. Also, an interface for the `Controller` would fix this.

Lastly, what about testing? Would it make more sense to include authorization when testing controllers, or not? I haven&#39;t quite started with testing yet since I&#39;m in the process of rebuilding the framework to be testable. 

Do you have any recommendations or opinions on where and how we could introduce authorization that doesn&#39;t raise the complexity? Or if we could use a more automated approach to the decorator pattern when using Convention over configuration?

Also, if you have any other suggestions on how to improve what I&#39;ve outlined, I would love to hear your thoughts.


