answers.body_markdown:
&gt;The problem is that Rust&#39;s test framework implicitly uses the built-in test library, which depends on the standard library. This means that we can&#39;t use the default test framework for our `#[no_std]` kernel.

[Phillip Oppermann&#39;s blog](https://os.phil-opp.com/testing/)

It&#39;s my understanding you&#39;ll need a custom framework. My answer is inspired from the quoted gentleman&#39;s blog.

1. Comment out or delete tests in `tests` directory.

2. Create `src/main.rs` with the following code.

```
#![feature(custom_test_frameworks)]
#![test_runner(crate::test_runner)]
extern crate nulloc;
//pub mod bump_heap;

fn main() {}

#[cfg(test)]
fn test_runner(tests: &amp;[&amp;dyn Fn()]) {
    println!(&quot;Running {} tests&quot;, tests.len());
    for test in tests {
        test();
    }
}

#[test_case]
fn fails() {
    assert_eq!(true, false);
}
```
FYI I commented out `pub mod bump_heap` because there are compiler errors.

3. Use nightly for running tests.

If you don&#39;t have rust nightly installed:

`rustup install nightly`

Run tests as nightly:

`rustup run nightly cargo test`

### Unit and integration tests

If you read through that linked blog, it goes into detail about how to do integration tests and whatnot. I suppose for the time being you could just use `mod` in main.rs or something for the sake of organization.

```
mod integration {
    use super::*;

    #[test_case]
    fn works() {
        assert!(true);
    }   
}

mod bump_heap_unit {
    use super::bump_heap;

    #[test_case]
    fn works() {
        assert!(true);
    }   
}   
```
